\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dependencies and setup**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether to run jdeps, but I need to focus on understanding the dependencies without extra codecs. The client artifact seems to include the original. For documentation, I should mention creating a PulsarClient with a serviceUrl, and connecting producers/consumers. The decision involves the docker_image and perhaps including the Testcontainers dependency. The user mentioned various setups for tests, and it sounds like I need to clarify how Docker images and dependencies interact. Should the tests start standalone using Testcontainers?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying guidance on dependencies**\\n\\nI’m looking at whether I should restate certain deterministic entries in the guidance. The user seems interested in setting up with a service URL and command for Docker. They asked about agent guidance regarding environment properties and test setups. While Docker-specific code guidance seems acceptable, I should avoid repeating entries. There's also a question about including the Testcontainers dependency, and whether to use a specific version of junit-jupiter for easier tests. But will the native-image build automatically incorporate additional dependencies? I'm not certain.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining test image and metadata**\\n\\nI’m considering how the native test image will work with testImplementation and if it includes Testcontainers. It seems I might need metadata for the dependencies. I see there’s existing metadata for org.testcontainers:testcontainers, potentially version 1.19.8, but the junit-jupiter version doesn’t have metadata. The generateMetadata function could include conditional metadata for test code and resources, but it may only mark test-specific metadata. Still, I'm unsure if the dependencies' metadata will behave the same way.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Docker and coverage 